This is a known .NET 10 breaking change. Android deprecated `adjustResize`, and MAUI .NET 10 adopted **edge-to-edge** rendering, so `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` no longer works. The fix is to react to **IME window insets** instead.

### In `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`:

```csharp
using Android.Views;
using AndroidX.Core.View;

protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)
{
    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);

    // Listen for keyboard (IME) insets on the root view
    var rootView = Window!.DecorView.FindViewById(Android.Resource.Id.Content)!;

    ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(rootView, new KeyboardInsetsListener());
}

private class KeyboardInsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
{
    public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(Android.Views.View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
    {
        var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
        var sysBarInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.SystemBars());

        // Use whichever is larger — keyboard or navigation bar
        int bottom = Math.Max(imeInsets.Bottom, sysBarInsets.Bottom);
        v.SetPadding(v.PaddingLeft, v.PaddingTop, v.PaddingRight, bottom);

        return insets;
    }
}
```

### Why this works

| .NET 9 (old) | .NET 10 (new) |
|---|---|
| `adjustResize` shrinks the window | Edge-to-edge: app draws behind keyboard |
| `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` | `WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime()` |

The insets listener fires whenever the keyboard opens/closes and gives you the exact pixel height, so you pad the root view to push your input bar above the keyboard.

### iOS

iOS still uses `adjustResize`-equivalent behavior by default via `UIScrollView` keyboard avoidance — no change needed there. If you do hit issues on iOS, wrapping your chat layout in a `ScrollView` is usually sufficient.
